<BODY><DIV class="wrapper bg "><DIV class="rootContainer"><DIV id="nzh-header"><DIV class="nzh-navigation" id="primaryNavContainer"><DIV class="nav-container"><DIV class="secondary"><DIV class="secondary-wrapper"><DIV class="subnav navcol" id="subnav_id22"><OL class="right"><DIV class="subnav navcol" id="subnav_id39"><OL class="right"><DIV class="midContent" id="articlePage"><DIV class="wrapper left"><DIV class="contentContainer left eight"><DIV class="storyHeader"><H1>Man burnt after cigarette ignites methylated spirit fumes</H1><DIV class="tools"><SPAN>5:19 PM Tuesday Jan 17, 2012</SPAN></DIV></DIV><DIV class="contentContainer left six nopad articleBody" id="articleBody"><DIV id="storyExtraContent"><DIV class="articleImage three" id="articleImage"><A href="#" onclick="s_objectID='articleimage';" class="imageLink"><DIV class="overlay"><SPAN class="text">Expand</SPAN></DIV></A><DIV class="caption"><H2>File photo / Thinkstock</H2></DIV></DIV></DIV><P>A Gisborne man is in hospital with moderate burns after a cigarette ignited fumes from an open can of methylated spirits.</P><P>

The 26-year-old was working in a shed at the back of his property in the suburb of Kaiti earlier this afternoon.</P><P>

He suffered burns to his right leg and arm.</P><P>

The Fire Service says the cigarette lit a shade cloth and a couch in the shed.</P><P>

They say it shows just how important it is to take care when lighting cigarettes around flammable liquids.</P></DIV></DIV></DIV></DIV></OL></DIV></OL></DIV></DIV></DIV></DIV></DIV></DIV></DIV></DIV></BODY></HTML>